	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Record Guyanese rice production and slight recovery in Haiti</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 February 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In November 2013 CARICOM confirmed that Guyanese rice production for 2013 would reach 529,384 tonnes – a 25.43% increase on the 422,057 tonnes produced in 2012. According to Guyana’s Ministry of Agriculture, this success was achieved as a result of “more land being brought under cultivation, and the provision of improved farming techniques with better seed varieties”, which has increased yields to over 5 tonnes/ha. The next target is 6 tonnes/ha. A stable price for Guyanese rice producers has also assisted efforts to expand rice production.</p><p>The progress made in 2013 increases the likelihood of the government reaching its 600,000-tonne target for national rice production before the scheduled date of 2020. However, the government has recognised that reaching this target will depend on finding favourably priced markets for Guyanese rice exports.</p><p>According to the Guyana Government Information Agency (GINA), the EU used to be the main market, but since a government-to-government agreement in 2012, “66% of Guyana’s rice paddy goes to Venezuela”, as a result of the higher prices available under this agreement. GINA commented that in 2013, Guyana would “supply 210,000 tonnes of rice and paddy to Venezuela under an agreement sealed in May [2013]”.</p><p>Guyana also supplies CARICOM markets. Jamaica is its largest export market, but a small amount is exported to Trinidad and Tobago. It is also exploring opportunities for exporting to Dominica, Haiti and possibly Panama.</p><p>Finding favourably priced markets for Guyanese rice is becoming more urgent, as rice prices have been falling steadily since November 2012. Average prices in October 2013 were 23.3% below the levels of November 2012, 26% below those of September 2011 and 29% below their peak in February 2009.</p><p>Meanwhile, USDA’s report of November 2013 noted a slight recovery in Haitian rice production following last season’s hurricane damage, with production forecast to reach 142,000 tonnes of paddy from some 85,000 hectares harvested. Rice plays an increasing part of Haitians’ daily diet: consumption in 2013/14 was projected to reach 490,000 tonnes of milled rice. Some 415,000 tonnes of imports took place in 2012, of which the US had a 97% market share.</p><p>Formerly, Haiti imported only small amounts of rice from Guyana. However, the conclusion of a major supply agreement with Vietnam in December 2012 for approximately 300,000 tonnes may well change the pattern of Haitian import sourcing: by July 2013 some 45,000 tonnes had been delivered in three shipments under this government-to-government agreement with Vietnam.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
