<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Rice%20Production%20and%20Trade%20Update_Santo%20Domingo_Haiti_11-7-2013.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Rice%20Production%...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The agreement between the governments of Guyana and Venezuela, within the framework of the Petro-Caribe Arrangement, has provided a much-needed stimulus for increased rice production in Guyana. However, with the expiration of the government-to-government agreement, Guyanese rice exporters will need to negotiate new supply contracts with Venezuelan importers if rice producers in Guyana are not to be confronted with the grim reality of lower and volatile rice prices in their two principal markets – CARICOM and the EU.</p><p>Price competition on Caribbean markets means that Guyanese exporters do little more than break even. Given the existing common external tariff for rice in CARICOM, the declining trend in international prices and the demands of CARICOM consumers for lower food prices, regional rice price prospects do not look good.</p><p>It remains to be seen what impact current developments will have on government efforts to further expand Guyanese rice production. If adverse production effects are to be avoided, efforts will need to focus on achieving cost efficiencies throughout the industry (through bulk sourcing of fertilisers and coordination and cooperation in the procurement and utilisation of capital equipment) and enhancing prices obtained, through value addition.</p><p>In terms of value addition, opportunities exist for forging linkages to food processors that use cereals as inputs, including in the brewing sector. Such opportunities are already being explored in Suriname. There may also be scope for marketing branded rice in smaller consumer-ready packages, and diversification into speciality rice production in line with evolving market trends.</p>
		</div>
		
